## ðŸ§  What Is an API & Why Is It Important?

An **API (Application Programming Interface)** allows two software systems to talk to each other.

Common real-world examples:

* Google Maps API â†’ Track delivery locations
* Payment APIs â†’ Online transactions
* ChatGPT API â†’ AI features in apps
* Email APIs â†’ OTPs & notifications

Without APIs, apps would not be able to exchange data or perform online services.


## âš™ï¸ How Does an API Key Work?

Most APIs require a **secret API key** to authenticate requests.

Think of an API key as
ðŸ‘‰ **a password used by software to identify itself**

When an app sends a request:

```
User â†’ App â†’ API Server
```

The request contains:

* API key
* Requested data
* App identity

If the key is valid â†’ the API processes the request.

So the API key must always stay **private and secure**.


## ðŸ—º Example: How Google Maps API Works

Many websites and apps use **Google Maps API** to:

* display maps
* calculate distance
* track delivery drivers
* show live location

### Real-world examples

* Swiggy / Zomato â€” delivery tracking
* Uber â€” live route navigation
* Real estate apps â€” property locations

Developers integrate Google Maps API directly into their app or website.
Each time the API is used, **the company is billed based on usage**.

For example (not exact pricing):

* Google CAPTCHA â†’ around $2
* Google Maps API â†’ around $7 (usage-based)

So if someone steals the API key and uses it heavily:

ðŸ‘‰ **the company pays the bill â€” not the attacker**

This leads to real financial loss.


## â— Why API Key Leaks Are Dangerous

If API keys are exposed publicly, attackers may:

* use paid services for free
* abuse billing
* access restricted features
* impersonate legitimate apps

This becomes a **financial + security risk**.

### How API keys leak

* hard-coded in public JavaScript files
* uploaded to public GitHub repos
* left inside debug/test builds
* forgotten during development


## ðŸ” My Learning: Detecting API Keys in JavaScript Files

As part of my cybersecurity learning journey, I explored how researchers detect exposed API keys â€” **ethically and responsibly**.

I used tools in **Kali Linux** to scan public JavaScript files.

---

### ðŸ›  Tool 1 â€” Pinkerton (finding JavaScript files)

Pinkerton helps locate JavaScript files used by a website.

#### Install Pinkerton

```
git clone https://github.com/ankane/pinkerton.git
cd pinkerton
bundle install
```

#### Run Pinkerton

```
[pinkerton https://target-website.com]
```

This lists all JavaScript files loaded by the target website.

> **Note:** I only test on legal and authorized targets.

---

### ðŸ§ª Tool 2 â€” gmapsapiscanner (Google Maps API key testing)

Once a key is identified, researchers check whether it is:

* active
* restricted
* or misconfigured

#### Install

```
git clone https://github.com/ozguralp/gmapsapiscanner.git
cd gmapsapiscanner
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

#### Run

```
python3 gmapsapiscanner.py -k YOUR_API_KEY
```

Results indicate if the key is:

* Safe
* Misconfigured
* Exploitable

